    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial breast, internal mammary; remember this drainage, it's key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A) Medial half of breast. The internal mammary lymph nodes are a primary drainage pathway for the medial breast, making their assessment critical in breast cancer staging and treatment planning.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage of the breast is complex but follows predictable patterns. The internal mammary lymph nodes, located along the internal mammary artery and vein, receive lymphatic fluid predominantly from the medial and central portions of the breast. This drainage pathway is particularly significant for tumors located in the inner quadrants, as involvement of these nodes can upstage the disease and influence adjuvant therapy decisions. Understanding this specific drainage pattern is fundamental for accurate surgical planning and prognosis in breast cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The lateral half of the breast primarily drains to the axillary lymph nodes, which are the most common site of metastasis for breast cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): While the internal mammary nodes are located within the anterior mediastinum, they do not primarily drain the mediastinal organs themselves; their main afferents are from the breast and anterior chest wall.\nOption D (Incorrect): The lungs drain to hilar, peribronchial, and mediastinal lymph nodes, which are distinct from the internal mammary chain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drainage Pathway | Primary Region Drained | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Axillary Nodes | Lateral breast, upper outer quadrant | Most common site of breast cancer metastasis, dictates axillary staging |\n| Internal Mammary Nodes | Medial breast, central breast | Important for inner quadrant tumors, can upstage disease, requires specific imaging/biopsy |\n| Supraclavicular Nodes | Advanced disease, often indicates distant spread | N3 disease, poor prognosis, often requires systemic therapy |\n| Cross-lymphatic Drainage | Contralateral breast, abdominal wall | Less common, indicates advanced disease or specific tumor locations |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial breast tumors = think internal mammary nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn PET-CT or dedicated breast MRI, enlarged or hypermetabolic internal mammary lymph nodes can be identified, indicating metastatic involvement. Intraoperatively, sentinel lymph node biopsy can sometimes be performed for internal mammary nodes, though it's technically more challenging than axillary node biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology: Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend considering internal mammary node evaluation, especially for medially located tumors or those with extensive axillary involvement, as it can impact staging and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Medial half of breast | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Lateral half of breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mediastinum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lungs | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Medial half of breast** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Applied Basic Anatomy And Physiology** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "A"
