    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Parietal cells: the stomach's acid factory, essential for digestion.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B) Parietal cells. These specialized cells within the gastric glands are solely responsible for the secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl), which is the primary acid component of gastric juice, and intrinsic factor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nParietal cells, also known as oxyntic cells, are located predominantly in the fundus and body of the stomach. Their apical membrane contains H+/K+-ATPase proton pumps, which actively transport H+ ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K+ ions. This process is highly energy-dependent and is regulated by histamine (via H2 receptors), acetylcholine (via M3 receptors), and gastrin (via CCK2 receptors). The high concentration of HCl creates an acidic environment crucial for protein denaturation, activation of pepsinogen, and defense against ingested pathogens.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chief cells secrete pepsinogen, the inactive precursor to pepsin, which is responsible for protein digestion in the stomach.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'G' cells, located primarily in the gastric antrum, secrete gastrin, a hormone that stimulates parietal cells to secrete acid.\nOption D (Incorrect): Goblet cells, found throughout the gastrointestinal tract, secrete mucus, which protects the gastric lining from acid and enzymes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Primary Secretion | Key Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| Parietal cells (Oxyntic cells) | Hydrochloric Acid (HCl), Intrinsic Factor | Gastric acidification, Vitamin B12 absorption |\n| Chief cells (Peptic cells) | Pepsinogen | Protein digestion (after activation to pepsin) |\n| G cells | Gastrin | Stimulates HCl secretion |\n| Goblet cells (Mucous neck cells) | Mucus, Bicarbonate | Gastric mucosal protection, lubrication |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Parietal cells pump protons; chief cells chew proteins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, conditions like peptic ulcer disease (PUD) or Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (ZES) are direct consequences of dysregulated acid secretion. In ZES, a gastrinoma (often in the pancreas or duodenum) can be localized by CT or MRI, leading to intractable ulcers and hypertrophic gastric folds due to excessive gastrin-stimulated acid production.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommends therapies that often target parietal cell function, such as proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), to reduce acid secretion and promote ulcer healing.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chief cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Parietal cells | ✅ Correct |\n| C | ‘G’ cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Goblet cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Parietal cells** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Applied Basic Anatomy And Physiology** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "B"
