    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 G cells make Gastrin; it's the gastric acid's main driver.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Gastrin. This question tests fundamental knowledge of gastrointestinal physiology, specifically the endocrine function of the stomach. Understanding the origin and function of key GI hormones is crucial for surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrin is a peptide hormone secreted primarily by G cells, which are located predominantly in the antrum of the stomach. Its main physiological role is to stimulate gastric acid secretion from parietal cells, both directly and indirectly by promoting histamine release from enterochromaffin-like (ECL) cells. Gastrin also plays a trophic role, stimulating the growth of the gastric mucosa. Clinically, excessive gastrin secretion, often due to a gastrinoma (Zollinger-Ellison syndrome), leads to severe peptic ulcer disease and diarrhea due to hyperacidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Histamine) (Incorrect): Histamine is secreted by enterochromaffin-like (ECL) cells in the gastric mucosa and acts as a potent stimulator of acid secretion, but it is not secreted by G cells.\nOption C (Pentagastrin) (Incorrect): Pentagastrin is a synthetic analog of gastrin, used pharmacologically to stimulate gastric acid secretion, but it is not a naturally secreted hormone.\nOption D (Secretin) (Incorrect): Secretin is a hormone secreted by S cells in the duodenum and jejunum, primarily in response to acidic chyme, stimulating bicarbonate secretion from the pancreas and inhibiting gastric acid secretion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Origin | Primary Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gastrin | G cells (gastric antrum) | Stimulates gastric acid secretion, mucosal growth |\n| Secretin | S cells (duodenum, jejunum) | Stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion, inhibits gastric acid |\n| Cholecystokinin (CCK) | I cells (duodenum, jejunum) | Stimulates gallbladder contraction, pancreatic enzyme secretion |\n| Histamine | ECL cells (gastric mucosa) | Potentiates gastric acid secretion |\n| Somatostatin | D cells (gastric antrum, duodenum, pancreas) | Inhibits release of many GI hormones, suppresses acid secretion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: G cells secrete Gastrin, stimulating Gastric acid.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor gastrinomas (Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome), somatostatin receptor scintigraphy (SRS, Octreoscan) is the most sensitive imaging modality to localize primary tumors and metastases. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the duodenum and pancreas, often with intraoperative ultrasound, is crucial to identify small tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guideline on the Diagnosis and Management of Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome (2019). Recommends localization studies like SRS for suspected gastrinomas and surgical resection when feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Histamine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastrin | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Pentagastrin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Secretin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Gastrin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Applied Basic Anatomy And Physiology** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "B"
