    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your porta hepatis; it's the liver's front door, not its back exit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D) Hepatic veins. This question tests your fundamental understanding of the anatomy of the porta hepatis, a critical landmark in hepatobiliary surgery. The porta hepatis is the hilum of the liver, where structures enter and exit the liver parenchyma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe porta hepatis, often referred to as the 'gateway to the liver,' contains the portal triad: the proper hepatic artery, the portal vein, and the common hepatic duct. These structures are encased within Glisson's capsule and are crucial for the liver's blood supply, nutrient delivery, and bile drainage. Their consistent anatomical arrangement is vital for safe surgical dissection, particularly during cholecystectomy or liver resections.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Portal vein is a major component of the portal triad, entering the liver at the porta hepatis to deliver nutrient-rich, deoxygenated blood.\nOption B (Incorrect): Common hepatic duct is part of the biliary tree, exiting the liver at the porta hepatis to drain bile.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic artery (proper) is a branch of the celiac axis, entering the liver at the porta hepatis to supply oxygenated blood.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Structure | Location/Function at Porta Hepatis | Direction of Flow |\n|---|---|---|\n| Portal Vein | Posterior, delivers nutrient-rich blood to liver | Afferent (into liver) |\n| Hepatic Artery | Anterior-medial, delivers oxygenated blood to liver | Afferent (into liver) |\n| Common Hepatic Duct | Anterior-lateral, drains bile from liver | Efferent (out of liver) |\n| Hepatic Veins | Exit posterior-superiorly from liver into IVC | Efferent (out of liver) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Porta hepatis has a triad: artery, vein, duct. Hepatic veins are separate.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring an open or laparoscopic cholecystectomy, the structures of the porta hepatis (cystic duct, cystic artery, common bile duct, hepatic artery, portal vein) are meticulously identified within Calot's triangle to prevent iatrogenic injury. On cross-sectional imaging like CT or MRI, the portal triad is clearly visible as three distinct tubular structures entering the liver hilum, while hepatic veins are seen draining directly into the IVC, separate from the porta.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guideline for the Surgical Treatment of Gallstone Disease (2010, updated 2016): Emphasizes critical view of safety, which relies on accurate identification of structures in the porta hepatis region to prevent bile duct injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Common hepatic duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatic veins | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Hepatic veins** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Applied Basic Anatomy And Physiology** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "D"
