    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, check behind the cecum!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Retrocaecal. This position is the most common anatomical variant for the appendix, accounting for the majority of cases, and understanding its prevalence is fundamental for diagnosing appendicitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe appendix exhibits significant anatomical variability due to its embryological development and rotation of the midgut. The retrocaecal position, where the appendix lies posterior to the cecum, is found in approximately 65-70% of individuals. This anatomical location is clinically significant as it can lead to atypical presentations of appendicitis, with pain potentially localized to the flank or back, and a lack of classic rebound tenderness due to the appendix being cushioned by the cecum and retroperitoneum. Awareness of this common variant is crucial for surgical trainees to avoid diagnostic delays.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Paracaecal) (Incorrect): The paracaecal position, where the appendix lies alongside the cecum, is a less common variant, occurring in about 1-2% of cases.\nOption C (Subcaecal) (Incorrect): The subcaecal position, where the appendix lies below the cecum, is also a less common variant, found in approximately 2% of individuals.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Appendix Position | Prevalence | Clinical Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Retrocaecal | 65-70% | Atypical pain, difficult palpation, often masked |\n| Pelvic | 20-30% | Mimics gynecological/urological issues |\n| Subcaecal | ~2% | Can be confused with right ureteric colic |\n| Paracaecal | ~1-2% | Lies alongside the cecum, variable presentation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Retrocaecal rules the appendix roost.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, the retrocaecal appendix lies posterior to the cecum, often obscured by bowel gas, making visualization challenging but identifiable by its blind-ending tubular structure. Intraoperatively, it requires mobilization of the cecum to visualize.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWSES (World Society of Emergency Surgery) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) emphasize the importance of imaging (CT/US) in diagnosing appendicitis, especially given anatomical variations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Which is the most common position of the appendix? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Paracaecal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Subcaecal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Retrocaecal | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Retrocaecal** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Appendix** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "D"
