    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Primary hypertension: No surgical fix, just lifestyle and meds.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the type of hypertension that is *not* surgically correctible. Primary (essential) hypertension, by definition, lacks a surgically treatable secondary cause, making it the correct answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary hypertension, also known as essential hypertension, accounts for the vast majority of hypertension cases and has no identifiable secondary cause that can be surgically addressed. Its pathophysiology is multifactorial, involving genetic predisposition, environmental factors, and complex interactions of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, sympathetic nervous system, and endothelial dysfunction. Surgical intervention is reserved for secondary causes of hypertension where a specific anatomical or endocrine abnormality can be resected or repaired, leading to a potential cure or significant improvement in blood pressure control.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Renovascular hypertension is often caused by renal artery stenosis, which can be surgically corrected through revascularization procedures like angioplasty with stenting or surgical bypass.\nOption B (Incorrect): Cushing syndrome, when caused by an adrenal adenoma or pituitary adenoma, can be surgically treated via adrenalectomy or transsphenoidal hypophysectomy, respectively, leading to resolution of hypertension.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pheochromocytoma, a catecholamine-secreting tumor, is a classic surgically correctible cause of hypertension, with adrenalectomy being the definitive treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Hypertension | Cause | Surgical Correctability |\n|---|---|---|\n| Renovascular | Renal artery stenosis | Yes (e.g., angioplasty, bypass) |\n| Cushing Syndrome | Adrenal/Pituitary adenoma | Yes (e.g., adrenalectomy, hypophysectomy) |\n| Pheochromocytoma | Adrenal medullary tumor | Yes (adrenalectomy) |\n| Primary (Essential) | Multifactorial, idiopathic | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always differentiate primary from secondary hypertension; only secondary causes are surgically correctible.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor secondary causes, imaging like CT angiography or MRA can reveal renal artery stenosis (renovascular), adrenal masses (Cushing's, pheochromocytoma), or pituitary lesions. Intraoperatively, a pheochromocytoma might appear as a well-encapsulated, highly vascular adrenal mass, often requiring careful handling due to catecholamine release.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation, and Management of High Blood Pressure in Adults: Emphasizes screening for secondary causes of hypertension, including renovascular disease, primary aldosteronism, Cushing's syndrome, and pheochromocytoma, especially in resistant hypertension or atypical presentations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Renovascular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cushing syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pheochromocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Primary hypertension | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Primary hypertension** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Arterial Disorders** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: Vascular Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "D"
