    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Infection + Diabetes = IV Insulin. No exceptions.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks how to control diabetes in the setting of infection. In this acute, stress-induced hyperglycemic state, short-acting insulin is the most appropriate choice for rapid and titratable glucose control.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfection causes a significant physiological stress response, leading to increased counter-regulatory hormones (e.g., cortisol, glucagon, catecholamines) which elevate blood glucose levels. Short-acting insulin, often administered via an intravenous infusion, allows for precise and immediate adjustment of glucose levels, minimizing the risks of both hyperglycemia (which impairs immune function and wound healing) and hypoglycemia. Its rapid onset and relatively short duration of action make it ideal for managing fluctuating glucose in critically ill or infected patients, where oral agents or long-acting insulins would be too slow or unpredictable.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Venous stasis is a circulatory condition, often a complication of diabetes, but it is not a method for controlling blood glucose in the setting of infection.\nOption B (Incorrect): Malignancy is a disease process entirely unrelated to the control of diabetes with infection.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option is part of the question stem, not a viable answer choice. The question asks 'Diabetes with infection should be controlled by which one of the following?', making 'Short-acting insulin' the direct answer to the implied question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Insulin Type | Onset | Peak | Duration | Use Case |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Rapid-acting (Lispro, Aspart) | 5-15 min | 30-90 min | 3-5 hours | Mealtime, correction doses |\n| Short-acting (Regular) | 30-60 min | 2-4 hours | 5-8 hours | Mealtime, IV infusions for acute hyperglycemia |\n| Intermediate-acting (NPH) | 1-4 hours | 4-12 hours | 10-18 hours | Basal coverage, often BID |\n| Long-acting (Glargine, Detemir) | 1-2 hours | No peak | 18-24 hours | Basal coverage, once daily |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute hyperglycemia in infection demands rapid, titratable control with short-acting insulin.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor diabetic foot infections, imaging (X-ray, MRI) may show gas in soft tissues, osteomyelitis (cortical destruction, periosteal reaction), or abscess formation. Intraoperatively, one would expect purulent discharge, necrotic tissue, and potentially exposed bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Diabetes Association (ADA) Standards of Medical Care in Diabetes - 2024. Recommends intravenous insulin infusion for critically ill hospitalized patients with persistent hyperglycemia (glucose >180 mg/dL) and for those with diabetic ketoacidosis or hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous stasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diabetes with infection should be controlled by which one of the following? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Short-acting insulin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Short-acting insulin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Arterial Disorders** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: Vascular Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "D"
