    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't face EMPD, check the apocrine zones!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Extramammary Paget's disease (EMPD) is a rare intraepithelial adenocarcinoma that predominantly affects apocrine-rich areas, making the face an uncommon primary site.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEMPD is characterized by the presence of Paget cells within the epidermis, often originating from apocrine gland stem cells or pluripotent epidermal stem cells. Its predilection for apocrine-rich regions, such as the anogenital area (vulva, perineum, scrotum, perianal region) and axilla, is a key diagnostic feature. While it can occur in other areas, the face is not considered a common site, distinguishing it from other dermatological conditions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): EMPD is indeed thought to arise from apocrine glands or their stem cell precursors, explaining its distribution in apocrine-rich areas.\nOption C (Incorrect): The perineum and anorectum are among the most common sites for EMPD, consistent with its apocrine gland origin.\nOption D (Incorrect): Clinically, EMPD can present as an erythematous, scaly, eczematous plaque, which can mimic other skin conditions, including squamous cell carcinoma in situ (Bowen's disease) or chronic eczema, making diagnosis challenging without biopsy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Extramammary Paget's Disease | Mammary Paget's Disease | Bowen's Disease (SCC in situ) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Location | Anogenital, axilla, eyelids | Nipple/areola | Sun-exposed skin, anogenital |\n| Underlying Malignancy | ~25-30% associated with underlying adenocarcinoma (GI, GU, apocrine) | ~90-100% associated with underlying breast carcinoma (DCIS or invasive) | Low risk of invasive SCC (3-5%) |\n| Cell Origin | Apocrine gland stem cells | Ductal carcinoma cells migrating to epidermis | Keratinocytes |\n| Histology | Paget cells (large, pale, vacuolated) | Paget cells (large, pale, vacuolated) | Atypical keratinocytes, full-thickness epidermal involvement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EMPD loves apocrine glands, not your face.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, wide local excision with frozen section control of margins is often performed due to the pagetoid spread of the disease. No specific imaging sign exists for the superficial disease itself, but imaging (e.g., CT, MRI) may be used to evaluate for underlying associated invasive adenocarcinoma, especially in the anogenital region.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Vulvar Cancer (v1.2024) provides recommendations for the diagnosis and management of extramammary Paget's disease of the vulva, including surgical excision and evaluation for underlying malignancy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Most common site is the face | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Arises from apocrine glands | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Occurs in the perineum and anorectum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Resembles squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Most common site is the face** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Breast** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: Breast Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "A"
