    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When facial nerve lesions lurk, MRI is the diagnostic perk!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is B, MRI scan. MRI is the gold standard for visualizing soft tissue structures like cranial nerves, making it ideal for detecting lesions affecting the facial nerve, whether inflammatory, neoplastic, or demyelinating.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMRI's superior soft tissue contrast allows for detailed visualization of the facial nerve's course through the temporal bone, cerebellopontine angle, and parotid gland. It can differentiate between various pathologies such as schwannomas, hemangiomas, and inflammatory processes like Bell's palsy or Ramsay Hunt syndrome. Specific sequences like T2-weighted imaging can highlight nerve edema, while contrast-enhanced T1 sequences are crucial for identifying enhancing lesions, providing critical information for diagnosis and surgical planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): CT scan is excellent for bony detail, such as the facial nerve canal, but offers poor soft tissue resolution for the nerve itself. It's useful for bony erosion or fractures affecting the nerve.\nOption C (Incorrect): Ultrasound has limited penetration for deep structures like the facial nerve within the temporal bone and is not suitable for comprehensive visualization.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cervical endoscopy is an endoscopic procedure used to visualize the pharynx, larynx, and upper esophagus, not the facial nerve.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Use | Facial Nerve Utility | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| MRI | Soft tissue, nerves, inflammation | Gold standard for nerve lesions, tumors, edema | Less ideal for bony detail, cost, availability |\n| CT | Bone, acute hemorrhage, fractures | Bony canal assessment, erosion, fractures | Poor soft tissue contrast for nerve itself |\n| Ultrasound | Superficial structures, vascular flow | Limited to superficial segments (e.g., parotid) | Poor penetration for intracranial/intratemporal segments |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MRI is for nerves and soft tissue; CT is for bones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, facial nerve schwannomas typically appear as enhancing lesions along the nerve's course, often with a 'dumbbell' shape if extending through bony foramina. High-resolution T2 sequences can show nerve edema in inflammatory conditions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) 2013 Clinical Practice Guideline: Bell's Palsy. Recommends MRI for atypical presentations or lack of recovery to rule out other causes of facial paralysis, including tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT scan\tB. MRI scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | C. Ultrasound\tD. Cervical endoscopy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Which is the most common tumour of the middle ear ? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) MRI scan** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Eye, Ear And Orbit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
    "verified_answer": "B"
